. Rank's monograph remains the classic application of Freudian theory to hero myths. In The Hero the noted English ethnologist Raglan singles out the myth-ritualist pattern in James Frazer's many-sided Golden Bough and applies that pattern to hero myths. Dundes, the eminent folklorist at the University of California at Berkeley, applies the theories of Rank, Raglan, and others to the case of Jesus. In his introduction to this selection from Rank, Raglan, and Dundes, Robert Segal, author of the major study of Joseph Campbell, charts the history of theorizing about hero myths and compares the approaches of Rank, Raglan, Dundes, and Campbell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHeroesxMythology. 0aHeroesxReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh1 aDundes, Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRaglan, Fitzroy Richard Somerset, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRaglan, Lord, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRank, Otto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegal, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691234229zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691234229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691234229.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK